'''George H.V. Cecil'''(1925-) Is the owner and operator of [[Biltmore Farms]], LLC. He is the grandson of [[George Washington Vanderbilt II]], the founder of the [[Biltmore Estate]]. George H.V. Cecil was educated in Europe and served in the [[British Navy]] from 1942-1946 during [[World War II]] before returning to Asheville, North Carolina. Upon his return to Asheville he took on leadership positions with [[Carolina Power & Light]], Memorial [[Mission Hospitals]], [[UNC Hospitals]], Multimedia, Inc., and First National Bank and Trust. He and his family have contributed significantly to the community in [[Asheville]] and throughout North Carolina. 

Upon the passing of his mother, Cornelia Stuyvesant Vanderbilt, George, as the oldest son, was given the choice of taking over Biltmore Dairy Farms or the [[Biltmore Estate]]. Leaving the Estate for his brother [[William Amherst Vanderbilt Cecil]], George chose to take ownership of Biltmore Farms which, at the time, was much more profitable. George has continued to grow Biltmore Farms, LLC, transforming it  into a profitable Real Estate, Homebuilding, Commercial and Hospitality business that serves the [[Asheville, North Carolina|Asheville]] and surrounding area.

He has a distinct legacy as a direct descendent of both [[William Henry Vanderbilt]] and, on his father's side, [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|William Cecil]], the chief advisor to [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth]] the 1st in the 16th century.


